1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:07,729
A student related this pertinent incident to me, explaining why he'll never again eat in a certain cafeteria.

2
00:00:08,240 --> 00:00:16,130
For lunch one day, the student began, I decided to try a new cafeteria that had just opened a couple of weeks before.

3
00:00:16,480 --> 00:00:22,449
Nickels and dimes are pretty important to me right now, so I watch what I buy pretty closely.

4
00:00:22,720 --> 00:00:27,890
Walking past the meat section, I saw some turkey and dressing that looked pretty good,

5
00:00:27,919 --> 00:00:30,850
and it was plainly marked 39 cents.

6
00:00:31,120 --> 00:00:37,330
When I got to the cash register, the checker looked at my tray and said $1.09.

7
00:00:37,600 --> 00:00:43,169
I politely asked her to check it again because my tally was $0.99.

8
00:00:43,439 --> 00:00:46,689
After giving me a mean glare, she recounted.

9
00:00:46,960 --> 00:00:49,409
The difference turned out to be the turkey.

10
00:00:49,520 --> 00:00:53,650
She had charged me $0.49 instead of $0.39.

11
00:00:53,840 --> 00:00:58,130
Then I called her attention to the sign which read $0.39.

12
00:00:58,480 --> 00:01:00,209
This really set her off.

13
00:01:00,400 --> 00:01:02,370
I don't care what that sign says.

14
00:01:02,480 --> 00:01:04,610
It's supposed to be 49 cents.

15
00:01:04,640 --> 00:01:05,169
See?

16
00:01:05,280 --> 00:01:07,489
Here's my price list for today.

17
00:01:07,679 --> 00:01:09,890
Somebody back there made a mistake.

18
00:01:10,080 --> 00:01:12,610
You'll have to pay the 49 cents.

19
00:01:13,200 --> 00:01:20,050
Then I tried to explain to her the only reason I selected the turkey was because it was 39 cents.

20
00:01:20,240 --> 00:01:24,370
If it had been marked 49 cents, I'd have taken something else.

21
00:01:24,960 --> 00:01:30,209
To this, her answer was, you'll just have to pay the 49 cents.

22
00:01:30,640 --> 00:01:34,689
I did because I didn't want to stand there and create a scene.

23
00:01:34,800 --> 00:01:38,449
But I decided on the spot that I'd never eat there again.

24
00:01:38,720 --> 00:01:45,409
I spend about $250 a year for lunches, and you can be sure they'll not get one penny of it.

25
00:01:46,159 --> 00:01:48,530
There's an example of the little view.

26
00:01:48,560 --> 00:01:53,890
The checker saw one thin dime, not the potential $250.

27
00:01:53,890 --> 00:01:55,409
3.

28
00:01:55,600 --> 00:02:02,610
The Case of the Blind Milkman It's surprising how people sometimes are blind to potential.

29
00:02:02,880 --> 00:02:08,370
A few years ago, a young milkman came to our door to solicit our dairy business.

30
00:02:08,640 --> 00:02:14,290
I explained to him that we already had milk delivery service and we were quite satisfied.

31
00:02:14,560 --> 00:02:19,250
Then I suggested that he stop next door and talk to the lady there.

32
00:02:19,600 --> 00:02:23,810
To this he replied, I've already talked to the lady next door,

33
00:02:23,919 --> 00:02:30,449
but they use only one quart of milk every two days, and that's not enough to make it worthwhile for me to stop.

34
00:02:31,040 --> 00:02:41,969
That may be, I said, but when you talked to our neighbor, did you not observe that the demand for milk in that household will increase considerably in a month or so?

35
00:02:42,159 --> 00:02:46,290
There will be a new addition over there that will consume lots of milk.

36
00:02:46,800 --> 00:02:51,090
The young man looked for a moment like he had been struck, and then he said,

37
00:02:51,360 --> 00:02:53,570
how blind can a guy be?

38
00:02:54,320 --> 00:03:03,090
Today, that same one quart every two days family buys seven quarts every two days from a milkman who had some foresight.

39
00:03:03,360 --> 00:03:11,330
That first youngster, a boy, now has two brothers and one sister, and I'm told there'll be another young one soon.

40
00:03:12,159 --> 00:03:14,130
How blind can we be?

41
00:03:14,480 --> 00:03:17,409
See what can be, not just what is.

42
00:03:18,000 --> 00:03:22,850
The school teacher who thinks of Jimmy only as he is, an ill-mannered,

43
00:03:22,850 --> 00:03:27,409
backward, uncouth brat, certainly will not aid Jimmy's development.

44
00:03:27,600 --> 00:03:33,890
But the teacher who sees Jimmy not as he is now, but as he can be, she'll get results.

45
00:03:34,480 --> 00:03:41,489
Most folks driving through Skid Row see only broken down stumble bums, hopelessly lost to the bottle.

46
00:03:41,840 --> 00:03:46,130
A few devoted people see something else in the Skid Rowite.

47
00:03:46,240 --> 00:03:55,489
They see a reconstructed citizen, and because they see this, they succeed in many cases in doing an excellent rehabilitation job.

48
00:03:55,489 --> 00:03:57,169
4.

49
00:03:57,520 --> 00:04:00,370
What determines how much you're worth?

